{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"38a20a7b-1452-4f00-b2df-4740a1e265e5","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create (or edit) `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for MCP).\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Make sure your MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` SDK's `AddMcpServer()` with stdio transport).\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect the server automatically. You can verify it's connected via the **MCP** icon in the Copilot chat panel.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2d0b7db8-ff74-45f9-b970-3fa615f0171c","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"5C37:3D597:1CE0447:1FFE05A:69FA936B"},"id":"064470ff-82bf-4f37-b50c-f73d7f42e812","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:03:46.564Z","parentId":"3bb07f1c-40ae-44e4-939a-1288092a1301"}
